    <div class="intro">
        <h2>Sales Policy</h2>
        <div class="divider"></div>
        <p>Nintendo Homebrew is a community for homebrew, console modding, troubleshooting, and technical discussion. It is not a marketplace, sales platform, escrow service, reseller directory, or transaction hub.</p>
    </div>
    <p>For that reason, Nintendo Homebrew does not support the buying, selling, trading, auctioning, brokering, or advertising of consoles through its Discord server, website, or other official community spaces. This includes modded consoles, unmodded consoles, console bundles, accessories, flashcarts, repair jobs, parts, games, game cartridges, and similar goods or services.</p>
    <h3>Why sales are not supported</h3>
    <p>We cannot verify the quality, condition, safety, or working state of any console, accessory or device (including games) offered by a community member. A seller may claim that a system is clean, functional, legitimately owned, properly modded, unbanned, free of faults, or suitable for a buyer's needs, but Nintendo Homebrew has no practical way to confirm those claims nor any desire to begin providing such a service.</p>
    <p>We also cannot verify the legitimacy of a sale. Staff cannot reliably determine whether an item is actually owned by the seller, whether it is being accurately described, whether payment will be handled honestly, whether shipping will occur, or whether the transaction complies with the expectations and laws relevant to the people involved.</p>
    <p>Allowing sales would also create the appearance that Nintendo Homebrew has inspected, approved, endorsed, or vouched for the seller, the buyer, the item, or the transaction. We do not want community members to treat the server, website, or staff team as conferring legitimacy on private sales.</p>
    <h3>No endorsement, middleman role, or dispute handling</h3>
    <p>Nintendo Homebrew will not act as a middleman, guarantor, referee, recovery agent, reputation system, payment adviser, or dispute resolution service for private transactions. If a sale goes badly, staff cannot recover money, force a refund, verify tracking, inspect evidence, or determine who is telling the truth.</p>
    <p>This policy protects the community as a whole. It avoids turning technical support spaces into sales channels, prevents moderation from being dragged into private disputes, and reduces the risk that members interpret ordinary conversation as official approval of a seller or listing.</p>
    <h3>What this means in practice</h3>
    <p>Members should not post console listings, ask others to buy a console from them, solicit offers, advertise paid modding or repair services, run price checks for the purpose of arranging a sale, or direct other members to private messages for a transaction arranged through Nintendo Homebrew spaces.</p>
    <p>General technical discussion remains fine. Members may ask about console models, hardware revisions, common faults, modding requirements, buying considerations, or how to identify whether a system is suitable for homebrew. The line is crossed when the discussion becomes an attempt to arrange, promote, validate, or complete a transaction.</p>
	<p>Generally speaking, members can also ask <i>how to prepare a console or accessory or game for sale</i>, such as whether it is prudent to remove CFW (usually not), how to clean or prepare a console or accessory or game for sale, etc. This counts as general advice about consoles/accessories/games and does not directly count as facilitating a sale. Should the conversation move into facilitating or encouraging a sale, it should be ceased.</p>
    <p>Any private sale arranged outside Nintendo Homebrew is entirely between the people involved. Nintendo Homebrew does not endorse it, does not verify it, does not accept responsibility for it, and does not provide support for disputes arising from it.</p>
	<h3>What about approved hardmodders, staff service providers etc?</h3>
	<p>Nothing is changing with regard to the existence of approved hardmodders and/or staff who offer modding services. Reasons include:</p>
	<ol><li>Approved hardmodders and staff have accountability, ie we know their real details and can contact them should we receive reports of poor service and practices.</li>
	<li>Approved hardmodders and staff have invested time and energy in the community, becoming part of it rather than trying to use it to make a quick buck.</li>
	<li>Approved hardmodders and staff have been vetted for quality of their work and alignment with server policies (such as not loading consoles with 100 frii gaems before sending it back, and not overcharging to exploit the community).</li>
	<li>Approved hardmodders and staff have generally been around for many years, or at least long enough for us to get an idea about who they are and how they operate.</li>
	<li>Approved hardmodders and staff have something to lose; community standing, approval, etc. Others tend more to want to exploit the community for money and have no motivation to provide a good, reliable service.</li></ol>
